Excess capacity and eﬃciency in the quota managed Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery Steven Rusta,⁎ a University of Tasmania – Tasmanian School of Business and Economics, Private Bag 84, Hobart, Tasmania 7001, Australia b Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies – Taroona, Private Bag 49, Hobart, Tasmania 7001, Australia Keywords: Excess capacity Capacity utilisation Eﬃciency Quota management Individual Transferable Quota Jasus edwardsii Controlling the emergence of new, and managing existing, ﬁshing capacity is of major concern to ﬁsheries managers and policymakers worldwide [41,15,14,46]. Excess capacity is prevalent in ﬁsheries where there are incentives for race to ﬁsh and race to invest behaviour by the ﬁshery's participants [56,30,40,48]. In terms of the overall ﬁshery, excess capacity occurs when the ﬁshing capacity signiﬁcantly exceeds the level of harvest that is observed from the ﬁshing ﬂeet, and this represents economic waste in the sense that the total harvest could be taken with a smaller investment in ﬁshing capacity [49,6,25]. Such waste not only raises the potential for the spill-over of ﬁshing eﬀort between ﬁsheries, but also signals opportunities for the improvement of the ﬁshery's performance. 1 The ITQ system is one form of incentive based system for ﬁshing regulation. Incentive-based systems involve the allocation of individual vessel quotas that are either based on the quantity of catch, or represent a speciﬁc spatial distribution of the harvest rights [1]. Systems of spatially distributed harvest rights are referred to as Territorial Use Rights for Fishing (TURFs), and allocate an exclusive right to catch ﬁsh from a given area of a ﬁshery. In quantity-based systems, each vessel quota represents the right to harvest some proportion of the TAC in the ﬁshery [24,8]. In quantity-based systems, vessel quotas may be non-transferable or transferable. When vessel quotas are non-transferable they represent an allocation of catch to individual vessels that cannot be purchased or sold by the operators [2]. When vessel quotas are transferable, the operators in the ﬁshery trade quota rights between themselves and thereby establish a quota market [20]. Incentive-based systems where vessel quota is both transferable and quantity based are commonly referred to as ‘ITQ systems’. The Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery has an ITQ system [29] which has been widely studied [3,18,27,58,57,13] since its inception in the 1998 quota year. ⁎ Corresponding author. Excess capacity is a major concern for ﬁsheries management worldwide. It is often argued that Individual Transferable Quota (ITQ) systems will enhance eﬃciency and alleviate problems of excess capacity. While improvements in eﬃciency have been observed, most empirical studies have found only modest changes in excess capacity as a result of such systems. Using a database of compulsory log-book information for the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery in Australia, from January 2000 to December 2013, this study presents the ﬁrst analysis to investigate the dynamic behaviour of both excess capacity and eﬃciency (i.e. technical and scale eﬃciency) in an industrialised ﬂeet after the introduction of quota management. The analysis revealed weak evidence for a prolonged adjustment in the ﬁshery following the introduction of an ITQ system. In addition, no marked changes in excess capacity were observed over the study period; and furthermore, there was no evidence for an increase in excess capacity during a period of non-binding Total Allowable Catch (TAC) when race to ﬁsh behaviour increased in the ﬁshery. The results suggest a limited ability of the ITQ system to alleviate levels of excess capacity in ﬁsheries in the long-term. Contents lists available at ScienceDirect Marine Policy 76 (2017) 55–62

improve both biological and economic outcomes for the ﬁshery [24,8,4]. An ITQ system ﬁrstly establishes a Total Allowable Catch (TAC) control that limits the ﬁshery's harvest, and then allocates a set number of transferable rights to the TAC that can be traded.1 Although contentious in the literature, it is often argued that the trade in these rights will encourage the transfer of ﬁshing eﬀort from less eﬃcient to more eﬃcient ﬁshers [20,42,38]. The reduction in vessel numbers that occurs as the less eﬃcient ﬁshers exit the ﬁshery also has the potential to reduce or eliminate levels of excess capacity. Since the total harvest of the ﬁshery is shared among fewer vessels, the production of the most eﬃcient vessels may approach their ﬁshing capacity and thereby reduce excess capacity. The reduction in vessel numbers, and accompanying decline in excess capacity, can occur quickly, or may be drawn out over a number of years, depending on factors such as the availability of alternatives for the incumbent ﬁshers or functioning of the quota sale and lease markets [21,54,59].

The success of ITQ systems at eliminating the race to ﬁsh depends on a number of factors, which include: eﬀective governance [28]; a strong monitoring, control and surveillance system [43]; and critically on implementing a binding TAC constraint [35,23,34]. When the TAC is non-binding, the ﬁshery can revert to a regulated open access or limited entry paradigm [13,35,23,34] in which the incentives for race behaviour are well known and lead to an increase in ﬁshing eﬀort [13,35]. Periods of non-binding TAC have been observed in the northern zone of the South Australian rock lobster ﬁshery [37,39], the Australian South Eastern Trawl Fishery [34,12], and also in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery [13]. Studies of these ﬁsheries overwhelmingly ﬁnd an increase in ﬁshing eﬀort due to the non- binding TAC and, in some cases, a decline in the total value of the harvest [34,12]. In the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery, Emery et al. [13] asso- ciated a period of non-binding TAC with an increase in the temporal concentration of ﬁshing eﬀort (i.e. pot lifts) and a decline in the price of ‘quota’ or ‘catch shares’. There are many non-ﬁshing quota owners in this ﬁshery who lease the right to harvest catch quota for a single ﬁshing season at the prevailing market price to ‘lease’ ﬁshers that operate vessels and take the catch [58,57]. When the TAC is non- binding, the drop in the lease price of quota allows the entry of latent vessels [13] that are operated by ﬁshers who normally cannot aﬀord to harvest at the higher constrained quota price.

A small number of studies have compared excess capacity and eﬃciency before and after the introduction of an ITQ system. These studies overwhelmingly ﬁnd evidence for only a small reduction in excess capacity following the introduction of such systems [11,53], although some do ﬁnd a more signiﬁcant change. For instance, Squires et al. [55] investigated excess capacity before and after the introduction of an ITQ system, and found reductions in excess capacity over a longer time period. In the case of eﬃciency, Soliś et al. [51] found that the introduction of quota management improved technical eﬃciency in the ﬁshing ﬂeet over time, and that these changes were likely due to the exit of ineﬃcient vessels and the easing of command and control regula- tions (e.g. trip limits and season length restrictions). Grafton et al. [22] also found that the short run eﬃciency gains from privatisation may take a number of years to materialise. However, none of these studies has directly investigated the temporal (i.e. dynamic) behaviour of excess capacity and eﬃciency in an ITQ-managed ﬁshery; nor was there any investigation of changes in excess capacity and eﬃciency during a period of non-binding TAC.

this paper applies Data Envelopment Analysis (DEA) to investigate the dynamic behaviour of excess capacity and eﬃciency in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery in Australia from January 2000 to December 2013. The Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery has been quota-managed since the 1998 quota year [29], and from the 2008 to the 2010 quota years was subject to a non-binding TAC [29,13]. Both technical and scale eﬃciency [7], as well as unbiased capacity utilisation [33], are measured for the ﬁshery over this period. The estimates are used to explore the relationship between excess capacity, eﬃciency and the race to ﬁsh, through investigating: (1) whether the ﬁshery's adjustment occurs over a lengthy period of time following the introduction of ITQs; and (2) if the pattern of excess capacity and eﬃciency reﬂects the increase of race to ﬁsh behaviour during a period of non-binding TAC. 2.1. Measuring capacity utilisation and eﬃciency This paper measures unbiased capacity utilisation as the ratio of the technically eﬃcient output for vessel j in season t divided by the (j,t)/ capacity output for that vessel in season t [33], i.e. CU(j,t)=YTE (j,t), where CU(j,t) is the vessel's unbiased capacity utilisation, YC (j,t) is its technically eﬃcient output and YC (j,t) is its capacity YTE Using compulsory log-book data,

output. Technically eﬃcient output refers to the maximum output that can be obtained from a given set of inputs when output is constrained by the availability of both the ﬁxed and variable inputs [7,17] and is measured using the output-orientated DEA approach as per Coelli et al. [7]. Output-orientated technical eﬃciency is measured at the same time as technical eﬃciency, according to this approach. Capacity output represents the maximum output that can be produced in a period of time, given normal or customary operating conditions, with existing plant and equipment and provided that the availability of variable factors is not restricted [44,32,31], and is also measured using the output-orientated DEA approach as presented in Färe et al. [16]. In both cases we assume the production technology potentially exhibits Variable Returns to Scale (VRS) [16,26]. Another eﬃciency measure used in the paper is the scale eﬃciency, which is a measure of the eﬃciency loss that occurs due to a deviation from the technically optimal production scale for a VRS production technology. We measure scale eﬃciency as the ratio of the VRS technically eﬃcient output to the Constant Returns to Scale (CRS) technically eﬃcient output [7]. The vertical distance between the VRS and the CRS technologies represents the amount of output that is foregone due to lower productivity at the current scale of operation. The use of output-orientated DEA is more practical for capacity measurement, but has the limitation that it assumes the output of individual vessels can be expanded for a given set of vessel inputs (which may not be the case in quota ﬁsheries, where catch is controlled). The alternative for measuring technically eﬃcient and capacity output is termed input-orientated DEA, and this method searches the production data for combinations of the data points that minimise the use of inputs for a given level of output. A practical issue arises with this approach in the case of capacity measurement, where the ﬁxed inputs of the ﬁshery are assumed to be static at the vessel level. 3. The Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery and data

3.1. The Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery Fishing for southern rock lobster (Jasus edwardsii) occurs across Southern Australia and is managed by diﬀerent state jurisdictions, including Victoria, South Australia and Tasmania. Entry to the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery is limited with 312 licenced operators in 2012–13 [10], however not all of these licences were active in the ﬁshery in that year and these do not constrain the catch (i.e. catch is limited through the price of quota, under normal conditions). On average from the 2009–10 ﬁshing season to the 2011–12 ﬁshing season there were 234 active vessels in the ﬁshery [29], which indicates the presence of latent eﬀort that has the potential to re-activate at low quota prices [13]. The commercial ﬁshing season for rock lobster runs from March to February, with a closure in place for the majority of the state in September, and for the whole state during October to protect moulting lobsters. The rock lobster ﬁshery has been subject to an ITQ system, supplemented by size limits and gear restrictions, since the beginning of the 1998 quota year [19]. The gear limit was raised from 40 to 50 pots per vessel at the time the ITQ system was introduced. To account for geographical variation in the ﬁshery, a single TAC for the commercial ﬁshery is set each year using a spatially-explicit model that divides the ﬁshery into the eleven stock assessment areas shown below. Settlement of larvae from the water column is unevenly distributed around the state and depends on factors including ocean currents [45]. The productivity of the ﬁshery also varies by region due to diﬀerences in growth and survival. In the 2011-12 ﬁshing season [29] the west coast stock assessment areas were responsible for 45.2% of the total catch of the ﬁshery. Those on the east coast recorded 28.7% of the catch and the stock assessment area surrounding King Island was respon- sible for 26.1%.

The rock lobster ﬁshery contains a number of diﬀerent industry Marine Policy 76 (2017) 55–62 Table 1 Definition of variables. typologies as a result of the quota market [57]. These include quota owners, who own and may or may not choose to ﬁsh their quota units, and lease ﬁshers, who must lease quota units in order to ﬁsh. All ﬁshers must hold at least one quota unit in order to maintain their ﬁshing licence, and need a minimum of ﬁfteen units to go ﬁshing. For lease ﬁshers, the remaining fourteen units can be obtained from a decen- tralised market for quota [58]. Quota owners are not required to ﬁsh, and since the beginning of the system there has been a growing trend towards a ﬁshery that is characterised by lease ﬁshers who are supplied by a group of non-ﬁshing quota owner investors [58,57]. The variables used for the analysis presented in this paper are shown in Table 1. The BIOMASS variable was obtained from data provided by the Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS). The remaining variables (VESS_ID, AREA, YEAR, MONTH, CREW, POTLIFTS, WEIGHT and OVERALL_LENGTH) were obtained from a database of daily log-book records for the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery that is maintained by the Tasmanian Department of Primary Industries, Parks, Water and the Environment (DPIPWE). These records represent a regular census of the ﬁshery, and were updated in 2000 to collect additional information that is used in this study. Monthly aggregates of this log-book data, within the 2000–2013 ﬁshing seasons, were analysed in this paper.

While the majority of the variables in Table 1 were available for each month of the quota year (i.e. from March to February), the BIOMASS variable, which represents the tonnes of stock above the minimum size limit that were available to the ﬁshery, was only available on a quota year level. Therefore, all monthly variables were aggregated by ﬁshing vessel (i.e. VESS_ID) within each quota year. This means that POTLIFTS represents the total number of pots lifted by a vessel during a quota year and WEIGHT represents the total weight of lobsters caught by that vessel during the quota year. The BIOMASS, OVERALL_LENGTH and CREW variables represent the average inputs for the vessel during the quota year. After aggregation and cleaning, the dataset consisted of 3120 observations. TAC, harvest and the number of vessels To understand changes in the ﬁshery over the study period, the total harvest, the average harvest, the biomass, the TAC and the number of active vessels in the ﬁshery are reported below in Panels (a) and (b) of Fig. 2.

Panel (a) of Fig. 2 shows the evolution of the biomass, harvest and TAC in the ﬁshery. These three variables follow similar patterns over the study period, with the total biomass building steadily until around the 2005 quota year, when it begins to decline. This decline in the biomass eventually leads to reductions in the total harvest of the ﬁshery, starting in the 2008 quota year and continuing into the 2009 and 2010 quota years. Panel (b) of Fig. 2 shows the number of vessels participating in the ﬁshery and the average harvest per vessel. During the ﬁrst eight years of the study period, from the 2000 quota year to the 2007 quota year, the number of vessels operating in the ﬁshery declined from 242 to 203 and the average harvest increased from 6.1 to 7.5 t. This trend of decreasing participation in the ﬁshery was reversed in the 2008 quota year when the TAC became non-binding, and a substantial drop in the price of quota encouraged latent vessels to re-enter the ﬁshery [13]. From the 2007 to the 2011 quota years the average harvest per vessel fell by 34.9%, and vessel numbers increased to near the level recorded in the 2000 quota year. By the 2013 quota year, the number of vessels had declined again to a low of 201 vessels (close to the level recorded in the 2007 quota year). The average harvest per vessel remained around 5.0 t, which was only 14.7% lower than at the beginning of the study period. It is also worth noting that, in the four years preceding the introduction of the ITQ system in 1998, there was an average of 334 vessels that actively harvested in the ﬁshery [29]. Directly after the introduction of the ITQ system, this number of active vessels dropped to 286, and the decline continued throughout the 1999 and 2000 quota years. In terms of vessel numbers, therefore, the ﬁshery's adjustment occurred mostly immediately following the introduction of the ITQ system during the 1998 to the 2000 quota years, which do not form part of the study period. 4.2. Capacity utilisation and eﬃciency in the ﬁshery 4.2.1. Unbiased capacity utilisation, technical eﬃciency and scale eﬃciency

One of the aims of this paper was to explore the evolution of excess capacity and eﬃciency in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery over a period following the implementation of an ITQ system. This involved analysing the behaviour of the mean, median and interquartile range of unbiased capacity utilisation, shown in Panel (a) of Fig. 3, and of the same measures for technical and scale eﬃciency, shown in Panel (b) of Fig. 3. The capacity output and technically eﬃcient output are also reported in Panel (a) of Fig. 3. As shown in Panel (a) of Fig. 3, capacity utilisation in the ﬁshery remained above 60.0% for the study period; and, over the entire study period, the mean capacity utilisation was approximately 73.0%. These levels of capacity utilisation suggest the most eﬃcient vessels in the ﬁshery cannot substantially increase their output by increasing use of variable inputs, and thereby point to a low level of waste in the ﬁshery after the introduction of the ITQ system. Panel (a) of Fig. 3 shows movements in the mean values of the elements of unbiased capacity utilisation, i.e. the technically eﬃcient output and the capacity output, which have declined over the study period by 2.3 and 2.5 thousand tonnes, or 17.0% and 23.0%, respectively. However, this decline was not monotonic, and there was a spike in capacity output in the 2005 quota year that coincided with a fall in capacity utilisation. Panel (a) of Fig. 3 also shows that the median capacity utilisation is always greater than the mean capacity utilisation, which indicates the presence of some vessels with very low capacity utilisation. With the exception of the 2011 quota year, the interquartile range (i.e. the dispersion) of the capacity utilisation was mostly stable. In the 2011 Marine Policy 76 (2017) 55–62

quota year the interquartile range contracted to 28.0% points, com- pared with an average of 39.1% points for the other quota years. This represents an increase in the homogeneity of the vessels in terms of their capacity utilisation, and possibly reﬂects a concentration of ﬁshing eﬀort among fewer harvesters. This could result from a rush to buy quota units when the TAC became binding again at the beginning of the 2011 quota year. Overall, the homogeneity of the vessels in the ﬁshery, with respect to capacity utilisation, was approxi- mately stable over the study period. As shown in Panel (b) of Fig. 3, both technical eﬃciency and scale eﬃciency displayed four years of consecutive increase from the 2000– 2004 quota years, not long after the introduction of the ITQ system. This may indicate that the ﬁshery was operating at an ineﬃcient scale (i.e. in a region of decreasing returns to scale) with low technical eﬃciency before the introduction of the ITQ system. Panel (b) of Fig. 3 also shows that the mean values of scale eﬃciency (80.0%) were higher than those of technical eﬃciency (60.0%) throughout the study period. This suggests that the ﬁshers were operating at close to the technically optimal production scale but were not technically eﬃcient over the study period. This would indicate that the productivity of the ﬁshery could be increased by improving the utilisation of variable inputs but not by changing the total use of ﬁxed inputs.

Panel (b) of Fig. 3 also shows that the mean technical eﬃciency is consistently greater than the median technical eﬃciency, which suggests a positive skew in the distribution of technical eﬃciency among the vessels. This could indicate the presence of some ﬁshers with better knowledge of the ﬁshery or the presence of distinct sub- ﬂeets (i.e. those ﬁshing from shallow inshore waters versus deeper oﬀshore waters). It is worth mentioning that market pressures over recent years have seen a majority of southern rock lobster harvests Fig. 3. being taken from inshore waters [36]. In relation to scale eﬃciency, Panel (b) of Fig. 3 shows that the mean scale eﬃciency is consistently below the median scale eﬃciency, which suggests there is a negative skew. Extreme values of scale ineﬃciency may reﬂect the presence of ﬁshers who are unable to lease as many units of quota as they desire in the decentralised market, or who are unable to purchase the capital they require. Also, the dispersion of scale eﬃciency seems to be lower at higher median values and higher at lower median values (the Pearson correlation coeﬃcient between the median and the interquar- tile range for scale eﬃciency is −0.7, compared with just 0.04 for technical eﬃciency). This might reﬂect diﬀerences in production technologies between vessels, so that a change in the ﬁshery's total harvest has a disproportionately large impact on the scale eﬃciency of some vessels. Finally, the dispersions of both technical eﬃciency and scale eﬃciency do not change markedly during the period of non- binding TAC, from the 2008 to the 2010 quota years. That is to say, the re-entry of latent vessels over this period has not altered the homo- geneity of the ﬂeet in terms of its scale or technical eﬃciency. On the whole, the period of non-binding TAC caused vessels in the ﬁshery to operate at a lower technical eﬃciency, but with about the same level of scale eﬃciency. The consistency of the scale eﬃciency over this period may reﬂect the per vessel pot limit that applies in the ﬁshery. 4.2.2. Capacity utilisation and eﬃciency during the period of non- binding TAC

A second aim of the paper was to investigate whether capacity utilisation and eﬃciency in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery declined during the period of non-binding TAC from the 2008 to the 2010 quota years. This was done by ﬁrst partitioning the ﬁshery's data into three distinct sub-periods, which correspond to the non-binding Marine Policy 76 (2017) 55–62 Table 3 Mean and standard deviation of capacity utilisation, technical efficiency and scale efficiency before (2000–07), during (2008–10) and after (2011–13) the period of the non-binding TAC. TAC (2008–2010), the quota years preceding the non-binding TAC (2000–2007) and the quota years following the non-binding TAC (2011–2013). The mean values and standard deviations of capacity utilisation, technical eﬃciency, and scale eﬃciency for these sub- periods are reported in Table 3. The proportion of the ﬁshery's TAC that was harvested in each sub-period is also shown in Table 3, from which it can be seen that the proportion of the TAC harvested in the 2008–2010 sub-period (91.9%) was markedly below that observed in the two other sub-periods (98.8% and 97.5%, respectively).2

The capacity utilisation increased only slightly over the three sub- periods in Table 3, and showed no evidence of decline during the sub- period corresponding to the non-binding TAC. Similarly, the scale eﬃciency remained unchanged between the ﬁrst and second sub- periods, also giving no indication of a decline as a result of the non- binding TAC. However, the scale eﬃciency fell by three percentage points in the last sub-period (2011–2013). The mean technical eﬃciency was around ﬁve percentage points lower in the sub-period corresponding to the non-binding TAC when compared with the ﬁrst sub-period. Table 3 also shows that the standard deviations of the estimates of capacity utilisation and eﬃciency were essentially un- changed over the three sub-periods. This conﬁrms that there was no change in the dispersion of these measurements across the individual vessels between the sub-periods, so that changes in capacity utilisation and eﬃciency seem to represent simultaneous changes among all vessels. To further explore how capacity utilisation and eﬃciency in a quota-managed ﬁshery are aﬀected by the TAC constraint, Table 4 reports the partial correlation of capacity utilisation, technical eﬃ- ciency and scale eﬃciency with both the TAC and the proportion of the TAC harvested in each quota year. The results show a particularly high correlation between technical eﬃciency and the proportion of the TAC harvested. This is consistent with conventional economic theory, which suggests that when the TAC is binding, so that a high proportion of the TAC is harvested, the ITQ mechanism will ensure that eﬀort is allocated to the most eﬃcient vessels, and thereby increase the mean technical eﬃciency in the ﬁshery. The next highest correlation is between the scale eﬃciency and magnitude of the TAC constraint. This suggests that the ﬁshery might on average operate in a region of slightly increasing returns to scale, so that when the total harvest of the

Capacity utilisation is negatively correlated with both TAC and the proportion of TAC harvested, indicating an increase in the utilisation of capacity among active harvesters when the total harvest of the ﬁshery declines. During a period of non-binding TAC, this could reﬂect vessels increasing their harvesting activity (i.e. shots per quota year) to take advantage of the low quota prices. Where there is a decrease in a binding TAC, on the other hand, the greater scarcity of the TAC may increase the quota price so that vessel operators take more shots per quota year to meet ﬁxed costs and maintain existing operating surpluses. Similarly, scale eﬃciency is weakly negatively correlated with the proportion of the TAC harvested. When the TAC becomes binding, the decision about the scale of ﬁshing is no longer made exclusively by the vessel operators, but is set by the ﬁshery's manager. As a consequence, some ﬁshers may no longer be able to determine the scale of their harvesting activities, and the mean scale eﬃciency of the ﬁshery declines. Finally, technical eﬃciency is weakly positively correlated with the TAC. This might indicate a dispropor- tionate increase in the harvest of ineﬃcient vessels as the total harvest of the ﬁshery increases, but could also reﬂect statistical variation over the study period.

This paper has investigated the implications for excess capacity and eﬃciency from the implementation of an ITQ system. It is often assumed that an eﬀective ITQ system will eliminate ineﬃcient vessels and reduce excess capacity in the ﬁshery. While improvements in eﬃciency have been widely documented [51,22,52,50], theory oﬀers limited guidance as to the adjustment pathway required for the reduction in excess capacity to occur. Furthermore, most empirical estimates of capacity utilisation before and immediately after the introduction of an ITQ system indicate only modest reductions in excess capacity [11,53]. This paper has measured excess capacity using the unbiased measure of capacity utilisation [33], and investigated changes in excess capacity and eﬃciency over a fourteen year study period in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery that closely followed the introduction of an ITQ system. The paper has also looked for evidence of increasing race behaviours in the excess capacity and eﬃciency measures of the ﬁshery when it temporarily reverted to a limited entry open access paradigm under a non-binding TAC [13,35,23]. The analysis in this paper has shown that the decrease in excess capacity over time, following the introduction of an ITQ system in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery, is limited. This paper has found weak evidence that the adjustment of the ﬁshery occurs over a prolonged time period following the introduction of an ITQ system. A period of increasing scale and technical eﬃciency from the 2000 to the 2004 quota years could indicate a delayed adjustment of the ﬁshery after the introduction of the ITQ system in 1998. A prolonged period of adjustment might also be evidenced by a steady decline in vessel numbers up to the 2007 quota year, after which the TAC became non- binding. However, no evidence is found for a marked change in capacity utilisation over the study period. Stock assessment reports for the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery [29] indicate that a large change in vessel numbers occurred immediately following the intro- Marine Policy 76 (2017) 55–62

duction of the ITQ system (i.e. from the 1998 to the 2000 quota years). This was due to a change in the maximum allowable pots per vessel, which increased from 40 to 50 pots. There is some limited evidence in other studies for reductions in excess capacity in the years immediately following the introduction of the ITQ system [11,53], and this may have been the case of the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery. However, the simultaneous change in both input and output controls at the inception of the ITQ system is likely to obfuscate the empirical measurement of change in capacity utilisation over this period. In addition, a period of non-binding TAC in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery, over which evidence of the well-known race to ﬁsh has been observed [13], was not associated with an increase in excess capacity. The latent capital that re-commenced harvesting during this period did not signiﬁcantly alter the ratio of the technically eﬃcient output (i.e. the output of the technically eﬃcient vessel) to the capacity output of the vessels in each category of overall length, and as a consequence the mean level of unbiased capacity utilisation did not change markedly. Therefore while ITQ systems have become an increasingly commonplace regulation in world ﬁsheries [9,5], the eﬀect of this management system on excess capacity in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery seems to have been negligible over the period examined in this study.

Finally, it is not clear whether the measured levels of capacity utilisation in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery represent proble- matic excess capacity or economically eﬃcient excess capacity (i.e. capacity that is maintained by ﬁshers to take advantage of the spatial and temporal heterogeneity of the resource). Such ‘eﬃcient’ excess capacity has been demonstrated in the case of a sole-owner ﬁshery with stochastic ﬂuctuations in recruitment by Poudel et al. [47]. Since capacity utilisation in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery did not substantially change during a period of non-binding TAC, when the race to ﬁsh increased in the ﬁshery, it is possible that the under- utilisation of capacity measured in the ﬁshery represents some eﬃcient level. However, it is also possible that a combination of the licence limitation and the per vessel pot limit have constrained the expansion of capacity during the non-binding TAC to that caused by the re-entry of latent vessels, and therefore prohibited further problematic excess capacity from appearing in the ﬁshery over that period.

The retention of ineﬃcient per vessel pot limit controls, despite the use of quota management, has been supported by the industry for three major reasons: ﬁrstly, it was felt that pot limits would avoid the consolidation of eﬀort among a small number of harvesters; Secondly, it was thought more vessels operating with fewer pots each would minimise spatial conﬂicts in the ﬁshery; and ﬁnally, less pots per vessel was believed to increase the average cost per pot thereby discouraging the depletion of some inshore areas. One avenue for further research may be to examine the optimising behaviour of individual ﬁshers in this industry, to determine the way in which they respond to conventional economic incentives. Also, the catchability of lobsters in the Tasmanian Rock Lobster Fishery can change dramati- cally within quota years, both spatially and temporally, as well as between quota years [60]. While some amount of the variation in the excess capacity and eﬃciency over the study period may reﬂect these changes, a second stage regression involving vessel level, social and demographic data might also reveal covariates that deepen the current understanding of harvesting behaviour in this ﬁshery.
